Hermiston pew was a little square box , dwarfish in proportion with the kirk itself , and enclosing a table not much bigger than a footstool . 
Thence he might command an undisturbed view of that congregation of solid plaided men , strapping wives and daughters , oppressed children , and uneasy sheep dogs . 
On this particular Sunday , there was no doubt but that the spring had come at last . 
It was warm , with a latent shiver in the air that made the warmth only the more welcome . 
The shallows of the stream glittered and tinkled among bunches of primrose . 
Vagrant scents of the earth arrested Archie by the way with moments of ethereal intoxication . 
His heart perhaps beat in time to some vast indwelling rhythm of the universe . 
By the time he came to a corner of the valley and could see the kirk , he had so lingered by the way that the first psalm was finishing . 
A tuft of primroses was blooming hard by the leg of an old black table tombstone , and he stopped to contemplate the random apologue . 
The voice of the aged Torrance within rose in an ecstasy . 
He could not follow the prayer , not even the heads of it . 
And he felt for old Torrance of the many supplications , of the few days a pity that was near to tears . 
Dandie's sister , sitting by the side of Clem in her new Glasgow finery , chose that moment to observe the young laird . 
Aware of the stir of his entrance , the little formalist had kept her eyes fastened and her face prettily composed during the prayer . 
It was not hypocrisy , there was no one further from a hypocrite . 
That was the game of female life , and she played it frankly . 
In reason he must admire her clothes , and it was possible that he should think her pretty . 
